What tends to make an applicant stand out at School_D:
- Academics: strong fundamentals and a clear pattern of steady effort (we’re less focused on “one perfect score” and more on consistent performance and growth). We also look for students who can explain how they learn—study habits, how they handle setbacks, and how they seek help.
- Activities/initiative: depth over quantity. Leadership is great, but so is sustained commitment (e.g., sticking with a club/team/project and taking on real responsibility). Starting something small—tutoring, a project, an event—also stands out.
- Character & fit: reliability, curiosity, and how you contribute to a community. We notice students who communicate respectfully, collaborate well, and take ownership when things get hard.

- Advising/check-ins: new students typically have structured check-ins early on to make sure workload, routines, and course placement are on track.
- Academic support: teacher office hours/extra help are built into the rhythm of the week, and we encourage students to use support early rather than waiting.
- Community integration: we intentionally help first-years plug into clubs/teams and peer groups; many students find their footing quickly through activities.

To help you assess fit concretely: what subjects or activities are you most excited to pursue next year, and what kind of support helps you most (frequent check-ins vs. more independence)? - **Consistency and follow-through** (meeting deadlines, steady effort over time).

- **Positive community contribution** (collaboration, respect, and getting involved).

To help you assess fit: what subjects do you most enjoy (or want to push yourself in), and are you looking for a faster-paced/competitive environment or one that balances rigor with a lot of guided support? Also—where does School_A currently sit on your list if you had to rank today?
